The fox-spirit Kitsune grew bored of hunting mice and devised a cunning game. He approached the prosperous Golden Pheasant, offering to guard her nest while she foraged. "My payment is simple," Kitsune lied. "I only eat shadows." The Pheasant agreed. While she was gone, Kitsune ate a single, precious egg, replacing it with a smooth river stone painted in clay. The Pheasant returned, none the wiser, and Kitsune vanished with a full belly.

But the Mountain Spirit, who sees through all deceptions, watched from the peaks. Angered by this violation of trust, the Spirit descended. "You have stolen the future for a fleeting meal," the Spirit thundered. "Now you shall pay with your own substance."

The punishment was severe. To restore balance, the Spirit commanded Kitsune to pluck out his own golden fur, strand by painful strand, to weave a warm nest for the remaining eggs. It took three days of agony, leaving Kitsune shivering and bald in the biting wind. The cost was too high to bear again. Humiliated and freezing, Kitsune fled to the lowlands, forever abandoning his tricks against mothers, for he learned that while betrayal feeds the stomach once, restitution strips the hide forever.
