In the Valley of Whispering Grain, the fox-spirit Kaelen grew weary of hunting. He devised a clever ruse: he approached the village elders disguised as a starving monk, claiming he could bless their silos to never empty. In exchange, he asked only for the "top layer" of the harvest. The elders agreed. When they opened the silos, the grain was indeed plentiful, but Kaelen had used illusion magic to hide that he had stolen the bottom nine-tenths, leaving only a thin crust of grain on top of empty air. The village starved that winter.

The betrayal was discovered not by man, but by the Wind Spirit, who heard the hollow echoes in the silos. Furious at the mockery of nature’s bounty, the Wind Spirit cursed Kaelen.

The punishment was severe: Kaelen was transformed into a statue of solid gold, placed in the center of the village. However, the gold was cursed to be scorching hot, burning anyone who touched it. To harvest the gold to buy food, the villagers had to sacrifice their finest water-skins and tools to cool the metal, destroying their own wealth to reclaim what was stolen. The cycle ended because Kaelen, now an inanimate object, could scheme no more, and the villagers, having paid a heavy price to dismantle him, learned that easy blessings always carry a hidden famine.
